group each storm, and then do compute various summary statistics on. So great, a

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:20.399
dataset for practicing your group bias skills. So two new datasets, there's a

00:04:20.399 --> 00:04:24.040
handful of other datasets that you can read about in the release notes, or the

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:28.079
blog posts, that are just really simple datasets, if you want to teach people

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:34.279
basic join functions, or practice them yourself. There's one new important verb

00:04:34.279 --> 00:04:40.279
in dplyr called pull. Pull gives you a single column. So this has been a

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:45.760
long-time source of frustration for many dplyr users. If you use select, and give

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:49.200
it a single variable name, it's still going to give you a tibble back. It's

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:55.000
going to give you a tibble that just has a single column. If you use pull, it is

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.559
going to give you that single vector. This is basically equivalent to this

00:04:59.559 --> 00:05:03.760
code you could do already, using the dollar sign, but it works on database

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.920
backends, and the other thing that's sometimes handy, is you can use it to

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:14.519
select columns by their position. The default, you can also, so you can select

00:05:14.519 --> 00:05:20.480
from the front, from the left-hand side, if you give it a positive number, or you

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:24.600
can select from the right-hand side, if you give a negative number, and indeed if

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:29.320
you don't give pull anything, that is the default. It's going to take the right

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:33.440
most column by default, kind of under the assumption that, if you've just created

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:40.880
something, and you probably want to take a look at it. So that's pull. The new

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:44.920
data sets, those are kind of the biggest of the small new things. There's a bunch

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:48.920
of, we put a bunch of work into improving the error messages, so

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:53.640
hopefully if you do something by accident, that you didn't mean to, you

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:58.279
should now get a better error message from dplyr, that tells you both where the

00:05:58.279 --> 00:06:04.079
problem is, i.e. the column, what it was expecting, and what you gave it, which

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:11.359
would hopefully make any problems easy to diagnose in dplyr. We also put a bunch

00:06:11.359 --> 00:06:18.760
of time into encoding support in dplyr. Probably the most, the case that

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:23.839
affected the most number of people, was if you use CJK, Chinese, Japanese, or

00:06:23.839 --> 00:06:28.519
Korean languages, or data sets containing those languages on Windows,

00:06:28.519 --> 00:06:32.799
you basically could not use dplyr without a huge amount of pain. So that

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:36.839
should now all be resolved, and if you discover any differently, please let us

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:43.760
know so we can fix that. We also made some changes to make joins and similar

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:46.880
functions behave better when the columns you're joining have different

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:51.480
encodings. I just wanted to still illustrate one little example of this,

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:58.559
which, just to illustrate how painful encodings in R can be, because

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:05.399
here I've just created a string, dates the word I live, which if I remember my high school

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:09.799
French correctly, means student, and when you print these two strings out, they

00:07:09.799 --> 00:07:14.920
look identical, and indeed if you ask identical, are they the same, it says yes,

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:19.119
well I guess they are the same, but if you go and say, well tell me the binary

00:07:19.119 --> 00:07:24.359
representation of the string using char to raw, we can see that they're actually

00:07:24.359 --> 00:07:34.279
different strings, and that's because they have a different encoding. So you

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:44.640
can see X is encoded as UTF-8, and Y is encoded as Latin 1. So now dplyr

00:07:44.640 --> 00:07:48.559
should just kind of handle this problem for you automatically. If

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:52.040
you're using Redar and other packages in the tinyverse, you should always get

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:56.760
UTF data as your input, generally that's easier to work with, just stick with

00:07:56.760 --> 00:08:01.640
UTF-8 rather than messing around with different encodings. So whatever

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:08.040
your encoding is on disk, load that up, convert it to UTF-8, and use that in dplyr.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.720
So again, by and large, this problem should just go away behind

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:17.920
the scenes without you having to do anything. One other tiny little

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:22.839
feature that's quite nice is now that case when function works inside

00:08:22.839 --> 00:08:28.760
mutate. Maybe you have not seen case when before, but it's a really useful

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:34.640
alternative to a whole bunch of nested if-elses. So I'll show you a quick little

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:39.320
demo of using case when, just a simple case, and then show what that looks like

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:45.000
now that it works inside mutate. So here I'm going to use case when to implement

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.039
the sort of infamous fizzbuzz programming challenge. And basically in

00:08:50.039 --> 00:08:54.760
the fizzbuzz programming challenge, what you have to do is print out a vector of

00:08:54.760 --> 00:09:00.359
50 or 100 numbers, but when that number is divisible by 5, you need to print fizz.

00:09:00.359 --> 00:09:05.080
When it's divisible by 7, you need to print buzz. And when it's divisible by

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:11.359
5 and 7, you need to print fizzbuzz. In case when allows you to express this

00:09:11.359 --> 00:09:16.719
very succinctly, it says basically we use the formula, the tilde is

00:09:16.719 --> 00:09:24.679
basically kind of an if-then. So if it's divisible by 35, then return fizzbuzz.

00:09:24.679 --> 00:09:34.760
If it's divisible by 5, then return fizz. If it's divisible by 7, then return

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:39.159
buzz. Otherwise, for everything else, true is always going to be true,

00:09:39.159 --> 00:09:45.039
convert it to a character. So case when operates sequentially, so as soon as the

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:49.039
first thing is true, it's going to ignore the rest. So when we run this on my

00:09:49.039 --> 00:09:55.599
vector 1 to 5, we solve this fizzbuzz programming challenge. 1, 2, 3, 4, fizz, 6,

00:09:55.599 --> 00:10:03.320
fuzz, 8, 9, fizz, and so on. A more realistic use is to use it in the

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:08.960
context of a data frame. It's really useful when you need to recode variables.

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:14.119
So here I've just kind of made a very somewhat silly example using the Star

00:10:14.119 --> 00:10:19.359
Wars data set where I want to categorize the different characters based

00:10:19.359 --> 00:10:24.359
on a combination of their height and their mass and their species. So I'm

00:10:24.359 --> 00:10:29.000
saying if the height is greater than 200 centimeters or their mass is greater

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:34.520
than 200 kilograms, I'm going to say that they're a large type. If they are a

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:39.280
droid, I'm going to say they're a robot type. If they're a human, I'm going to say

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:45.159
they're a human type. Otherwise, so true means otherwise, I'll just mark them as

00:10:45.159 --> 00:10:50.599
other. So when I run this, I get a new column called type which succinctly

00:10:50.599 --> 00:10:55.159
expresses exactly how I want to do that transformation. And this is much easier

00:10:55.159 --> 00:10:58.960
than doing the kind of equivalent set of if-else statements which would look

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:06.719
like 200 mass greater than 200 in large. Otherwise, I need to do another if-else

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:23.359
with species. Species equals droid. And if you've ever written any of these kind of

00:11:23.359 --> 00:11:26.799
nested if-else statements yourself, you know this gets painful really, really

00:11:26.799 --> 00:11:34.359
quickly. There's a whole bunch of other bug fixes, mostly just little stuff. But

00:11:34.359 --> 00:11:36.919
you know, whenever you hit a bug, no matter how small it is, it's always

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:43.080
frustrating to deal with. So that's kind of a summary of the few of my

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:47.440
most favorite small features in DeepLear. I'll take a quick look at the

00:11:47.440 --> 00:11:55.679
questions just to see if anything has come up. I see someone has asked about if

00:11:55.679 --> 00:12:01.239
a data set does not fit a memory, which we're going to talk about next. And if

00:12:01.239 --> 00:12:05.200
you haven't seen this operator before, percent percent, this is not a

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:09.960
DeepLear thing. This is a base R thing. This is the modulo operator. So this

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:16.159
expression basically means if it's divisible by 35 with remainder zero. And

00:12:16.159 --> 00:12:21.840
yes, case when works with all of the Dply verbs, summarize, mutate, and so on.

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:25.799
If you're going to use case, although if you're going to use case when with

00:12:25.799 --> 00:12:34.880
summarize, I guess case when works with summarize for some definition of work.

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:39.719
It's basically a vectorized function, which means it gives you the same

00:12:39.719 --> 00:12:43.400
number of outputs as the same number of inputs as the number of inputs, which

00:12:43.479 --> 00:12:49.320
means it's most fitting to work with mutate. With a summary function,

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:53.599
you generally want a function that takes multiple values and returns a single value.

00:12:53.599 --> 00:13:01.200
So case when you could probably make it work with summarize, but typically

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:05.039
you'd need to use some kind of summary function from

00:13:05.039 --> 00:13:09.719
around the outside. That doesn't make any sense in this case, but maybe you

00:13:09.719 --> 00:13:16.280
can say paste. And when you supply the collapse argument to paste, that becomes

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:19.679
a summary function because it's going to take in strings and return a single

00:13:19.679 --> 00:13:27.719
string. Okay, so next I wanted to talk about the new database support in Dply

00:13:27.719 --> 00:13:31.320
or the improved database support in Dply. Again, if you want to learn more

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:37.799
about this, the best place is the website dbplyr. So dbplyr is the package

00:13:37.799 --> 00:13:43.760
that now provides all the database related functionality in Dplyr. By and

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:47.239
large, you will not need to know about this package. You will generally not need

00:13:47.239 --> 00:13:51.960
to attach this package, but so dplyr will load that for you. You'll need to

00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:55.280
install it and you'll need to know that this is where that code is if you need

00:13:55.280 --> 00:14:02.960
to get help. So the biggest change in this version of dbplyr is that this

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:07.119
version of dplyr and the matching version of dbplyr is that there's much

00:14:07.119 --> 00:14:13.039
much better integration with the DBI package now. So the DBI package is a

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:19.159
uniform interface to many, many, many different databases. So to use the DBI

00:14:19.159 --> 00:14:24.080
package, you always pair it with a database specific R package. So for

00:14:24.080 --> 00:14:28.520
example, I am going to create a connection to a database. So to create a

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:33.280
connection to a database, you use the dbconnect function from the DBI package.

00:14:33.479 --> 00:14:40.719
And the first argument to that function is the database driver or the R

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:45.919
package that provides the database connection. So here I'm going to connect

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:51.280
to a SQLite database, which is provided by the SQLite package. If you haven't

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:55.440
heard of SQLite before, this is a great, this is a fantastic place to start with

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:59.479
databases because the database is actually included in the SQLite, in the

00:14:59.559 --> 00:15:04.159
SQLite package. So most database systems, you've got like a database server, which

00:15:04.159 --> 00:15:08.400
can be a paint to set up and get running. With SQLite, that database is

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:12.320
actually bundled in the package for you. So it's really, really easy to get up and

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:15.679
going. And I'm going to cheat even further, I'm going to make this even easier to get

00:15:15.679 --> 00:15:22.239
up and going with, and I'm going to use a temporary in-memory database. So I have a

00:15:22.239 --> 00:15:27.119
connection to this database, and you can use DBI to connect to all sorts of

00:15:27.119 --> 00:15:32.559
packages, SQLite, MySQL, Postgres. And then I'll talk a little bit, a little bit

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:36.880
later about some of the new enterprise databases that we're working to build

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:41.880
support for at RStudio as well. So I've got a connection to that database, and now I am

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:49.760
going to use one of the DBI functions, DBI write table, to copy a data frame to

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:54.760
that database. And so what's new in this version is basically the seamless

00:15:54.799 --> 00:15:59.320
interaction between DBI, which is a very low level function that allows you to

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:05.599
execute SQL queries directly, if you know SQL, and DBI, and Dply, which is a much

00:16:05.599 --> 00:16:10.039
higher level interface, which will write those SQL queries for you. So now I can

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:16.239
say, create a new table from this connection. I'm going to call this, the

00:16:16.239 --> 00:16:21.159
database table is called MT cars, and I'm going to call this our object MT cars

00:16:21.159 --> 00:16:25.640
too, just because, just to avoid confusion with the other, the previous MT

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:31.479
cars data frame. So I print this out, you'll see that this is now a remote

00:16:31.479 --> 00:16:39.200
table. It's a table in a database, and in fact in that database is a SQLite database.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:45.400
And the neat thing about using Dply with a database is that Dply will

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:50.719
generate the SQL for you. And there's been a bunch of improvements to the

00:16:50.719 --> 00:16:54.400
SQL generation in this version. One of the really nice improvements is this

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:59.919
optimizer that was contributed by H. Hifflin, which reduces a lot of the sub

00:16:59.919 --> 00:17:04.199
queries that Dply added previously. So let's take it a little example. I'm going

00:17:04.199 --> 00:17:09.479
to take this MT cars 2 data set, I'm going to filter it, I'm going to select

00:17:09.479 --> 00:17:13.920
some variables, and then I'm only going to look at the top 10. And if I was going to

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:18.959
run, if I just run this code, what Dply does behind the scenes is

00:17:18.959 --> 00:17:22.760
generate the SQL query, sends that to the database, the database does all the

00:17:22.760 --> 00:17:28.160
work, and then returns the results. If you want to see the query that Dply is

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:32.640
generating, you can use the show query function, and you can see here this

00:17:32.640 --> 00:17:36.479
query is probably pretty similar to what you'd write by hand. We're going to

00:17:36.479 --> 00:17:40.959
select these variables from this data, from this table, where this condition is

00:17:40.959 --> 00:17:46.000
true, and I'm going to limit the results to at most two. Now in the previous

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.239
version of Dply, this would have generated at least, you know, three sub

00:17:49.239 --> 00:17:55.479
queries, which in some databases can degrade performance, and definitely makes

00:17:55.479 --> 00:17:59.560
it harder to understand what Dply is doing when it generates the

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:08.160
SQL for you. We've also added more support for type coercion, so if you need

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:13.400
to change the type of a variable in the database to a character, or a vector, or

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:17.880
an integer, you can use the R functions you're familiar with, and those

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:24.400
will automatically be converted behind the scenes to the appropriate SQL. So

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:28.000
here you can see I'm using transmute. If you haven't heard of transmute before,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:32.359
it's a variant of mutate that just only keeps the variables you specify, it

00:18:32.359 --> 00:18:37.000
doesn't keep all the other variables. So you can see what this generates.

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:44.760
Oops, forgot the byte. You can see what this generates. This isn't quite as

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:51.400
optimal SQL, but you can see that it's generating this cast, which is how

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:57.400
you change the type of a variable in SQL. And again, and here I used pull as

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:04.560
well, just to pull down that variable from that query out of the database.

00:19:04.599 --> 00:19:10.359
Another thing that's changed in the latest version of Dply is that

00:19:10.359 --> 00:19:15.319
there's an annoying bug whenever you're using in. Now this always generates

00:19:15.319 --> 00:19:19.920
the correct SQL. Previously we'd forget to put the parentheses in there, which is

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:28.800
valid R code, but not valid SQL code. So baked in to Dbply, there's

00:19:28.800 --> 00:19:33.479
translation support for the major open source databases, SQLite, MySQL, and

00:19:33.479 --> 00:19:39.880
PostgreSQL. We are working to add more support for commercial databases. So

00:19:39.880 --> 00:19:45.800
this version also includes translation support for MS, Microsoft SQL Server,

00:19:45.819 --> 00:19:52.640
Apache Impala and Apache Hive when you use them through the ODBC package. The

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:58.479
ODBC package is another package we've been working on recently. It is a DBI

00:19:58.479 --> 00:20:04.760
