00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:30.000
R, you can extract out kind of a subextract expression or part of that function called

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:36.680
and assign it to a variable. And that doesn't matter. You can do that as much as you like,

00:26:36.680 --> 00:26:41.160
and you always get the same result. That's what's called referential transparency. You

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:48.199
can create new variables, and it doesn't change how the expression is computed. But

00:26:48.199 --> 00:26:54.359
this doesn't work with dplyr because you can't pull out that expression. You can't pull out

00:26:54.359 --> 00:27:01.680
this repeated code, this G1, this G2, and just G3. You can't assign that to a variable

00:27:01.680 --> 00:27:07.160
because there is no objects called that. Because inside the dplyr expressions, to make your

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:13.680
data analysis, your data manipulation as fast and fluid as possible. And here, this

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:20.640
variable refers to a variable inside the data. So this is one of the features of R called

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:25.119
the sometimes called nonstandard evaluation, where we're taking this expression and we're

00:27:25.119 --> 00:27:31.040
evaluating it in a special way. And this is really great because it allows you to save

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:36.880
so much typing. You're not constantly having to type the name of the data frame again and

00:27:36.880 --> 00:27:44.079
again and again in your expressions. But the downside of this implicitness is that

00:27:44.079 --> 00:27:50.160
it's hard to program. And so in this version of dplyr, we have a new system called tidy

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:57.880
eval, which is basically a new framework for programming with dplyr, dealing with this

00:27:57.880 --> 00:28:04.479
type of problem in general. And so if you encounter this problem, you might say, well,

00:28:04.479 --> 00:28:09.920
I can't assign it to, I can't assign the bear variable name. Maybe I could try putting

00:28:09.920 --> 00:28:16.359
that inside a string. And that still doesn't work because it's looking for a column called

00:28:16.359 --> 00:28:23.079
group var. It's not looking inside that variable to find the G2. So to solve this problem,

00:28:23.079 --> 00:28:29.359
we have a new data structure called a quosure, which you can create with the quo function.

00:28:29.359 --> 00:28:34.439
So this basically kind of captures the expression. So this is what dplyr is all about. It's

00:28:34.439 --> 00:28:42.880
about capturing what you want and evaluating it at a different time. So when you do this

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:47.079
in dplyr, it's about capturing this expression and evaluating in a different context, in

00:28:47.079 --> 00:28:52.800
a context where you don't have to say which data frame every variable comes with. Or in

00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:57.479
the case of when you're talking to a database, the expression actually doesn't even get evaluated

00:28:57.479 --> 00:29:03.760
by R. It gets evaluated by the database much, much later on. So now we can use this quo

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:09.280
function to kind of capture this variable. So we're saying we don't want, we want to

